      "description": "The CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump was evaluated across five flow-speed operating points (3–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Predicted RH values ranged from 0.71 to 0.94, all satisfying the RH < 1.0 acceptance criterion. The validation narrative references the Thamsen et al. (2015) steady-flow VAD bench dataset as the experimental basis for comparison, noting strong agreement in mean shear stress magnitude and normalized hemolysis index across the overlapping flow-rate range (4–6 L/min). The Thamsen dataset employs the same FDA generic pump geometry and identical NIH hemolysis measurement protocol, lending apparent methodological continuity. Agreement metrics (NRMSE = 0.08, R² = 0.91) are reported as evidence of model fidelity. The narrative does not examine whether the steady-flow, non-pulsatile VAD operating conditions of the Thamsen dataset are appropriate for validating hemolysis predictions in the pulsatile, lower-afterload CPB context declared in the COU, where transient shear exposure history — not peak shear magnitude — is the dominant driver of erythrocyte damage. No comparedAgainst reference is recorded for this result.",
